<subSubSection lastPageId="21" lastPageNumber="22" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="20.[264,1325,1541,1887]" box="[264,402,1541,1566]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis box="[264,402,1541,1566]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Description</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[264,1325,1541,1887]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
Similar whip­like growth form (
<figureCitation box="[691,775,1581,1607]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="20.[264,367,1396,1420]" captionTargetBox="[302,1284,446,1372]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[302,1285,446,1372]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 12. Esperiopsis flagrum sp. nov. a, Holotype in situ at 955 m depth in Amchitka Pass. b, holotype after collection. c, Long fusiform styles and microscleres. d, Microscleres overview: large and small categories of isochelae and sigmas." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/173022/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
Fig. 
<number box="[746,775,1581,1607]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="12.0">12</number>
</figureCitation>
a, b) as known from the genera 
<taxonomicName box="[1158,1323,1581,1606]" class="Demospongiae" family="Cladorhizidae" genus="Asbestopluma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1158,1323,1581,1606]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Asbestopluma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[317,593,1621,1646]" class="Demospongiae" family="Guitarridae" genus="Euchelipluma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="elongata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[317,593,1621,1646]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Euchelipluma elongata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[603,699,1621,1647]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[603,699,1621,1647]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, described above. The 
<typeStatus box="[984,1086,1621,1647]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">holotype</typeStatus>
was broken in half during collection but the specimen had a total length of 
<quantity box="[986,1069,1661,1687]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.4" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" unit="cm" value="54.0">54 cm</quantity>
. This specimen was encrusted near its base with the demosponge 
<taxonomicName authority="Koltun, 1958" authorityName="Koltun" authorityYear="1958" box="[826,1261,1701,1727]" class="Demospongiae" family="Coelosphaeridae" genus="Lissodendoryx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="oxeata">
<emphasis box="[826,1086,1701,1726]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Lissodendoryx oxeata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Koltun" box="[1099,1261,1701,1727]" pageId="20" pageNumber="33" refString="Koltun, V. M. (1958) Cornucaspongia of sea waters washing the South Sakhalin and the South Kurile Island region. Issledovaniya dal´nevostochnykh morei SSSR, 5, 42 - 77, figs. 1 - 25. (in Russian)." type="journal article" year="1958">
Koltun, 
<number box="[1199,1261,1701,1727]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" value="1958.0">1958</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. The specimen is a beige, cylindrical sponge, tapering towards the top end, beset with numerous whitish thin processes, 
<quantity box="[559,664,1781,1807]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" unit="mm" value="4.0" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="3.0">3–5 mm</quantity>
in length, elastic but somewhat stiff. The diameter, without the whitish filaments, is 
<quantity box="[682,757,1821,1847]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" unit="mm" value="4.0">4 mm</quantity>
at the base, 
<quantity box="[929,1026,1821,1847]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" unit="mm" value="2.5">2.5 mm</quantity>
at the tip. This axis is compressible, elastic but resilient.
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/173023/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" targetBox="[302,1284,314,1305]" targetPageId="21">
<paragraph blockId="21.[264,1322,1317,1375]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[264,408,1317,1341]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">FIGURE 13.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[415,630,1318,1341]" class="Demospongiae" family="Esperiopsidae" genus="Esperiopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="flagrum" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[415,630,1318,1341]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Esperiopsis 
<taxonomicName box="[546,630,1318,1341]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" rank="species" species="flagrum" status="sp. nov.">flagrum</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[638,723,1317,1341]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[638,723,1317,1341]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
a, backside of large isochela. b, Small isochela. c, Side view of small isochela. d, Large and small sigmas.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="21.[264,1325,1427,1773]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Skeleton: There is no special ectosome developed. The central axis of the longitudinal sponge consists of interwoven polyspicular tracts of styles with many microscleres in between. Single tracts are 
<number box="[572,675,1507,1533]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="375.0" valueMax="600.0" valueMin="150.0">150–600</number>
µm in diameter. The lateral processes are supported by single polyspicular tracts running into them. The outermost layer of the processes and the longitudinal axis consists of densely arranged microscleres.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[264,1325,1427,1773]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Spicules: Megascleres are fusiform styles (
<figureCitation box="[862,955,1627,1653]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="20.[264,367,1396,1420]" captionTargetBox="[302,1284,446,1372]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[302,1285,446,1372]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 12. Esperiopsis flagrum sp. nov. a, Holotype in situ at 955 m depth in Amchitka Pass. b, holotype after collection. c, Long fusiform styles and microscleres. d, Microscleres overview: large and small categories of isochelae and sigmas." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/173022/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Fig. 
<number box="[926,955,1627,1653]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="12.0">12</number>
</figureCitation>
c), 
<number box="[1020,1137,1627,1653]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="1150.0" valueMax="1320.0" valueMin="980.0">
980– 
<date box="[1080,1137,1627,1653]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="1320-10-20" valueMax="1320-10-28" valueMin="1320-10-20">1320</date>
</number>
x 
<number box="[1185,1258,1627,1653]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="24.0" valueMax="28.0" valueMin="20.0">20–28</number>
µm. Microscleres are large, palmate isochelae (
<figureCitation box="[773,870,1667,1693]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="20.[264,367,1396,1420]" captionTargetBox="[302,1284,446,1372]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[302,1285,446,1372]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 12. Esperiopsis flagrum sp. nov. a, Holotype in situ at 955 m depth in Amchitka Pass. b, holotype after collection. c, Long fusiform styles and microscleres. d, Microscleres overview: large and small categories of isochelae and sigmas." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/173022/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Figs. 
<number box="[841,870,1667,1693]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="12.0">12</number>
</figureCitation>
d, 
<number box="[911,940,1667,1693]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="13.0">13</number>
a), 
<number box="[989,1076,1667,1693]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="105.0" valueMax="112.0" valueMin="98.0">98–112</number>
µm, small, palmate isochelae (
<figureCitation box="[392,491,1707,1733]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="21.[264,368,1317,1341]" captionTargetBox="[302,1284,314,1305]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[302,1285,314,1307]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 13. Esperiopsis flagrum sp. nov. a, backside of large isochela. b, Small isochela. c, Side view of small isochela. d, Large and small sigmas." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/173023/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Figs. 
<number box="[462,491,1707,1733]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="13.0">13</number>
</figureCitation>
b, c), 
<number box="[576,649,1707,1733]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="35.5" valueMax="43.0" valueMin="28.0">28–43</number>
µm, small sigmas (
<figureCitation box="[892,979,1707,1733]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="21.[264,368,1317,1341]" captionTargetBox="[302,1284,314,1305]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[302,1285,314,1307]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 13. Esperiopsis flagrum sp. nov. a, backside of large isochela. b, Small isochela. c, Side view of small isochela. d, Large and small sigmas." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/173023/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Fig. 
<number box="[950,979,1707,1733]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="13.0">13</number>
</figureCitation>
d), 
<number box="[1033,1106,1707,1733]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="18.5" valueMax="20.0" valueMin="17.0">17–20</number>
µm, large sigmas (
<figureCitation box="[273,357,1747,1773]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="21.[264,368,1317,1341]" captionTargetBox="[302,1284,314,1305]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[302,1285,314,1307]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 13. Esperiopsis flagrum sp. nov. a, backside of large isochela. b, Small isochela. c, Side view of small isochela. d, Large and small sigmas." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/173023/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Fig. 
<number box="[328,357,1747,1773]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="13.0">13</number>
</figureCitation>
d), 
<number box="[403,476,1747,1773]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="42.5" valueMax="48.0" valueMin="37.0">37–48</number>
µm.
</paragraph>
